@startuml 17-cascading-failures
title JOTP: Cascading Failures & Multi-Level Recovery
skinparam backgroundColor #f0f0f0
skinparam sequence {
    BoxBackgroundColor LightBlue
    LifeLineBorderColor DimGray
    LifeLineBackgroundColor White
}

participant Client
participant "L1 Supervisor\n(root)"
participant "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"
participant "Worker A"
participant "Worker B"
participant "Worker C"

autonumber

note over Client, "Worker C"
  Multi-level supervision tree with ONE_FOR_ALL strategy
  L1 (root) supervises L2 (service), plus other branches
  L2 (service) supervises 3 workers: A, B, C
end note

Client ->> "Worker A": send(message)
activate "Worker A"

note right of "Worker A"
  Worker A handling request
  ...
end note

"Worker A" ->> "Worker A": !! Unhandled Exception !!
activate "Worker A"

note right of "Worker A"
  Crash occurs
  Exception propagates
end note

deactivate "Worker A"

"Worker A" ->> "L2 Supervisor\n(service)": DOWN signal (crashed)
deactivate "Worker A"
activate "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"

note right of "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"
  L2 detects crash via link/monitor
  Strategy: ONE_FOR_ALL
  → must restart ALL children
end note

"L2 Supervisor\n(service)" ->> "Worker B": terminate()
activate "Worker B"
deactivate "Worker B"

"L2 Supervisor\n(service)" ->> "Worker C": terminate()
activate "Worker C"
deactivate "Worker C"

note right of "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"
  All children killed
  (cascading down)
end note

"L2 Supervisor\n(service)" ->> "L1 Supervisor\n(root)": DOWN signal
activate "L1 Supervisor\n(root)"

note right of "L1 Supervisor\n(root)"
  L1 detects L2 crash
  L1 strategy: ONE_FOR_ONE
  → restart only L2 (not siblings)
end note

deactivate "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"

"L1 Supervisor\n(root)" ->> "L2 Supervisor\n(service)": spawn replacement
activate "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"

note right of "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"
  L2 restarted with new instance
  (old state lost, reset to init)
end note

"L2 Supervisor\n(service)" ->> "Worker A": spawn(init, handler)
activate "Worker A"
deactivate "Worker A"

"L2 Supervisor\n(service)" ->> "Worker B": spawn(init, handler)
activate "Worker B"
deactivate "Worker B"

"L2 Supervisor\n(service)" ->> "Worker C": spawn(init, handler)
activate "Worker C"
deactivate "Worker C"

note right of "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"
  All children restart cleanly
  Process tree restored
  Message queue drained
end note

deactivate "L2 Supervisor\n(service)"

"L1 Supervisor\n(root)" ->> Client: service restored
deactivate "L1 Supervisor\n(root)"

note right of Client
  Recovery complete
  Total latency: ~200µs
  (before load balancer timeout)
  Message ordering preserved
  in new worker instances
end note

---

note over Client, "Worker C"
  KEY INSIGHT: Why cascading works
  1. Isolation: L2 failure doesn't kill L1 siblings
  2. Atomicity: L2 restart is atomic (all-or-nothing)
  3. Causality: Effect of crash = restart at that level
  4. Fast: Virtual threads enable rapid restarts
  5. Type Safety: New instances are sealed (no corruption)
end note

@enduml
